  "prompt": "Does Yemen support Private Military Contractors?",
  "response": "Yemen's official stance on private military contractors (PMCs) is complex due to the ongoing conflict and the fragmented nature of authority in the country. The internationally recognized government of Yemen, led by President Abdrabbuh Mansur Hadi until 2022 and later by a Presidential Leadership Council, has not explicitly endorsed or widely employed PMCs. However, due to the civil war and the influence of various local and international factions, there have been reports of PMCs being involved indirectly.\n\nFor instance, countries such as the United Arab Emirates (UAE), which is part of the Saudi-led coalition supporting the Yemeni government, have reportedly hired PMCs for specific operations in Yemen. These contractors are said to provide a range of services, including training, strategy, and direct combat support.\n\nThe chaotic situation on the ground, with multiple groups and interests at play, means that while the official Yemeni government might not openly support PMCs, their presence and activities in the country can sometimes be indirectly sanctioned or overlooked by different factions, including foreign powers involved in the conflict.",
